-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Bamburi, CFC Stanbic, Naiade Resorts, Savannah
-- Ana Monteiro
-- 2010-08-06T16:11:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-08-06/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-bamburi-cfc-stanbic-naiade-resorts-savannah.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  gained for a
fifth day, rising 0.2 percent to 1,743.08 at the 1:30 p.m. close
in Port Louis, the highest since Feb. 4.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  climbed 0.1 percent to 81.36 at the
3 p.m. close in Nairobi, taking its weekly gain to 5.1 percent,
the biggest since the week ending March 12. The  Nigerian Stock
Exchange All-Share Index  gained less than 0.1 percent to
25,738.79 at the 1 p.m. close in Lagos, according to the
exchange’s website.  
 Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  dropped 1.3 percent to
779.53 at the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek, while the  Ghana Stock
Exchange All-Share Index  retreated 0.3 percent to 6,222.96 at
the 1 p.m. close in Accra.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Bamburi Cement Co.  (BMBC KN) fell 4 shillings, or 2
percent, to 201 shillings. That’s the biggest drop since July
19. The Kenyan unit of Lafarge SA said first-half profit fell 22
percent to 2.44 billion shillings ($30.67 million) from a year
earlier as prices of cement dropped.  
 CFC Stanbic Ltd.  (CFCB KN), the Kenyan unit of Standard
Bank Group Ltd., gained 2 shillings, or 2.3 percent, to 88
shillings, the highest since Oct. 2, 2008. First-half profit
climbed 47 percent to 725.3 million shillings in the six months
through June.  
 Naiade Resorts Ltd.  (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
advanced 0.7 rupee, or 2.7 percent, to 27 rupees, the highest
since June 26. The company signed an agreement to sell the
buildings of the Hotel Le Recif on Reunion island, while it will
continue to market and manage the hotel.  
 Savannah Sugar Estates Co.  (SAVA MP), a Mauritian sugar
grower, rose to the highest in 15 years, gaining 20 rupees, or
3.5 percent, to 590 rupees, on expectations it will benefit
after buying a stake in the Villas Valriche property
development, AXYS Stockbroking Ltd. said.  
